The paper discusses the theoretical properties of Generative Adversarial Imitation Learning (GAIL), which is a machine learning approach for sequential decision-making policies. This topic is relevant to several sub-categories of computer science, including machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), robotics (cs.RO), systems and control (cs.SY), and computer vision (cs.CV). Given that the paper focuses on both the statistical and computational aspects of GAIL, it is likely to be classified under one or more of these sub-categories.
